<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Document</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ood and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rink </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ederation (FDF)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This written evidence is submitted by the Food and Drink Federation, the trade association for food and drink manufacturing. Food and drink is the largest manufacturing sector in the UK (accounting for 15% of the total manufacturing sector) turning over £78.7bn per annum; creating GVA of £20bn and employing up to 400,000 people.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Food security is fundamental, not only to individual well-being but to all wider human social and economic activity. It is also an extremely complex issue dependent on many different factors and variables. UK food security cannot be seen in isolation from what is happening elsewhere in the world. But, as the Committee recognised in its 2009 inquiry, there is potential for us to do more at a national level to address the challenges which have since been comprehensively articulated in the Final Report of the Government Office for Science Foresight Global Food and Farming Futures Project</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> published in January 2011.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In essence these challenges involve producing more, from less and with less impact against a background of world population growth, increased pressure on natural resources and the need to mitigate and adapt to climate change.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Other contributory drivers such as increasing urbanisation, demand for higher protein diets in developing countries and the apparently more frequent incidence of extreme weather events, notably droughts and floods, are widely recognised as reinforcing the need for greater resilience and sustainability across the whole food system, in terms of both production and consumption.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Food and drink manufacturing plays an essential role in driving resource efficiency and supplying consumers with a wide range of safe, nutritious, appetising and affordable products, as well as contributing to economic growth and supporting rural and other communities by offering many different employment opportunities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But improvements are needed at all stages of production, from the raw materials we source, to the energy, water and other resources we use in processing, through to helping consumers in the choices they make.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Science and technology have the potential to make a major contribution to the innovation required to make food which is healthier, more sustainable and more affordable for everyone.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Food and Drink Federation is the voice of the UK’s food and drink manufacturing industry. Our goal is to supply consumers with safe, nutritious, appetising and affordable food and to help them make healthier and more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sustainable choices which will secure these benefits for the future. We have a shared vision</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with Government to deliver 20% sustainable growth in our sector by 2020, for which innovation and skills will be key drivers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Through our Five-fold Environmental Ambition</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, launched in 2007, we have successfully delivered substantial improvements in resource efficiency as well as absolute reductions in carbon emissions, food and packaging waste, water and transport in our UK processing operations, while still increasing output to meet growing dema</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd, here and in export markets.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In response to growing awareness of the wider global challenges facing the food system (for example the Cabinet Office “Food Matters” report</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in 2008 and the Defra work on Food 2030</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in 2010) we reviewed and extended our Ambition (ahead of the launch of the Foresight report in 2011) to improve sustainability and resilience in our supply chains and to manage risk, including in respect of authenticity and traceability. We have also published separate guidance on saving water and the sustainable sourcing of raw materials and are developing further on-line support tools.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Since the publication of the Foresight report, we have been active participants in the Defra Green Food Project</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and in similar work at European level in the Sustainable Consumption and Production Roundtable</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We are also engaged in WRAP’s Product Sustainability Forum</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to promote the use of life-cycle analysis techniques across the value chain and take forward the concept of developing a circular economy where waste is viewed as a resource and re-use and recycling become the norm.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our work on product reformulation, food science and safety, nutrition and labelling is helping to improve health and well-being and support a better understanding of the complex relationship b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etween diet and sustainability.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We believe that a competitive and sustainable UK food and drink manufacturing sector has the potential to make a real contribution to future food security and green growth by producing more, from less and with less environmental impact, both as a major customer for a more productive UK agriculture and as part of global supply chains and markets.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our views on the Committee’s specific questions are set out below.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">How best to improve UK (and EU) food security, including using resources more efficiently</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is already a substantial body of analysis, at UK, EU and international level of the main challenges and what needs to be done to address them. What are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">currently lacking are delivery mechanisms for many of the actions required and an overarching strategic framework within which producers, processors, retailers, policy makers, regulators, consumers and other stakeholders can work together to drive collective improvements in performance.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Following the publication of its Roadmap to a Resource Efficient Europe</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in 2011, the European Commission is in the process of preparing a Communication on Sustainable Food, which is expected to be published in the first half of 2014. In our response to the associated public consultation exercise between July and October this year (the results of which are not yet available) we reiterated the need for a wider systems approach, taking account of the global context in which food production operates and the enormous complexity and inherent natural variability involved. Food security is also inextricably linked with water and energy security, which reinforces the case for a high level strategy.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In our response we also referred to the work we are doing with WRAP on resource efficiency and waste reduction as part of our own Five-fold Environmental Ambition and to the outcomes of the Defra Green Food Project. There are many other relevant current initiatives, including the UK Global Food Security</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> project and the Food Research Partnership resilience report</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> published in 2012, as well as Defra work on climate change adaptation</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Indeed the proliferation of different reports is itself symptomatic of the current fragmentation at policy level. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This fragmentation is compounded in terms of the research landscape. Although the recently published UK Strategy for Agricultural Technologies</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is based on the need to feed growing populations, here and globally, it does not specifically address priorities for food manufacturing or related work in respect of diet and nutrition. Defra did commission a study of these requirements from consultants A D Little, but the findings do not yet appear to have been taken forward. FDF has been working to produce an Innovation Vision for food manufacturing which aims to complement the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Agri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-Tech strategy and give a whole chain perspective.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition there is evidence, here and at EU level, of disconnect between food and industrial policies. Europe 2020</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, for example, looks at employment, innovation, education, social inclusion and climate change/energy, without explicit reference to food security, which necessarily underpins all other forms of economic and social activity. The UK’s Industrial Strategy</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> identifies agriculture as a priority area, but without extending this to the whole value chain.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Environmental Audit Committee report on sustainable food</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in April 2012 found that Government does not yet have a strategy that unifies policy areas that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">impact on food production, supply and demand in a way that drives the system as a whole towards greater sustainability. It also concluded that relying on markets to direct where basic science needed to improve was likely to fail. We believe those findings remain valid.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The relationship between the price of food and the cost of producing it</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Profit margins for food and drink manuf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">acturers are in general slightly lower than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">those of most other manufacturing sectors. This suggests that the prices they receive (which are usually from wholesalers or retailers rather than direct from final consumers) reflect a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t best a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> normal commercial return on their raw material, labour, energy, transport, marketing a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd other input costs. More broadly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the UK is considered a highly competitive market for food, with efficient distribution </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and retail systems </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and a variety of domestic and international supply chains. Raw material costs can, however, account for a substantial proportion of certain products and increases as a result of volatility in commodity markets often have to be absorbed by manufacturers as the market does not allow these to be passed on. The cost of food as a percentage of disposable household income</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s has also declined fairly steadily over the last 100 years, though it continues to account for a higher proportion of expenditure for those on low incomes (around 17% compared to an overall average of 10%).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Costs of production at farm level also vary quite significantly according to the size and efficiency of the producers concerned. Prices paid for agricultural raw materials are, however, set by market forces</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> often at global level. There will inevitably be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> differen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ces of view</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as to how equitably revenues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are shared within supply chains and how those chains should function.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> FDF supports both the Grocer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Supply Code of Practice</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the appointment of an Adjudicator</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to oversee its operation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The much more difficult question for food production is the extent to which the monetised costs of production reflect the wider associated resource costs and impacts. There is a growing body of academic work on this issue, but analysis is often complicated by the length and complexity of the supply chains involved and the lack of reliable metrics, particularly in respect of issues such as biodiversity, de-forestati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on, water and soil quality etc.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">FDF recognises that much more needs to be done to understand and address these issues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The implications of volatility in global food supply and demand for UK food security</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Even if the UK were to achieve higher self-sufficiency in those categories where it has productive capacity, our relative lack of scale in terms of world production and the nature of the open international trading system mean that we cannot be insulated from fluctuations in global supply and demand and their consequent impacts on price. Those impacts can be mitigated to some extent by forward </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">buying or hedging arrangements or by contracting for supply on a longer term basis, though smaller companies may be less able to manage risk in those ways. Investment in the resilience of supply chains, particularly for key raw materials or ingredients, also has a role to play. But these are essentially commercial decisions for individual businesses, as neither the UK nor the EU currently have policies to intervene directly in market operations (with some exceptions under the provisions of the Common Agricultural Policy) in a way which would make price or supply independent of wider global movements.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The potential value and contribution of science and GM technology to UK food security</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Getting “smarter with science” will be fundamental to raising the limits of sustainable production, addressing new threats, driving resource efficiency throughout the food supply chain and making food safer, more nutritious and affordable for all, not least through innovations in formulation, packaging and storage as well as improvements in plant and animal genetics and the functioning of primary agriculture.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">FDF has collaborated with the Food Sector Working Group of the Technology Strategy Board’s Biosciences Knowledge Transfer Network to identify a set of pre-competitive research priorities for the food and drink industries to ensure an innovative, resilient, resource-efficient and safe manufacturing supply chain for now and generation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s to come. These priorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> form the core of our own </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Innovation Vision</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for unlocking the potential of science to drive improvements in resource efficiency and promote sustainable growth.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">FDF is also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">co-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sponsoring a new Centre of Excellence for Food Engineering</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at Sheffield Hallam University to help bridge the gap between basic and applied research and promote technology transfer. This will complement the work of the Centre for Innovative Manufacturing which is a joint initiative of Nottingham, Birmingham and Loughborough Universities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition FDF is a founder member of the National Technology Platform for Food</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which is part of the European Technology Platform Food For Life programme</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">On the specific issue of GM, FDF believes that modern technologies, including genetic modification, offer considerable potential to improve the quality and quantity of food supply and could also enhance sustainability through better resource use. But we recognise that the impacts of such technologies have to be objectively assessed through scientific investigation and that robust controls may be needed to protect consumers and the environment. Consumer understanding through education and information will also be fundamental to public acceptance and consumers also need to be given the choice to buy other products if they so wish. We think t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he time has come for a free,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">science-led </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">debate on these issues.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">How food and farming supply chains, and the current systems for traceability can contribute to increased resilience</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">FDF’s guidance on Sustainable Sourcing: Five Steps</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Towards Managing Supply Chain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Risk</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> sets out key questions which need to be considered. We are also about to launch further guidance on traceability and authenticity</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to help protect businesses from food fraud following events earlier this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> year in relation to horsemeat.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">More generally, many companies are now aware of the extent to which they rely on their supply chains and that increasing resilience will bring them competitive advantage to meet customer needs. There are several good examples of companies investing in their supply chains, both here and in third countries, to ensure the quantity and quality of the supplies they need.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Certification schemes also have a role to play, for example in respect of commodities like palm oil or in relation to sustainable fisheries. Whether or not as part of a formal certification or supplier audit, full traceability and chain of custody considerations also play an extremely role in relation to food safety, product recalls and other forms of incident management.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Whether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food security strategies and planning</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In July 2013, Defra published its National Adaptation Programme</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for making the country more resilient to climate change. This covered actions in seven policy areas (built environment, infrastructure, health, agriculture and forestry, natural environment, business and local government) but with no explicit objectives in relation to food production or food security, other than the resilience of (domestic) agricultural production. Infrastructure improvements and raised awareness of risk among businesses in general (including food and drink manufacturing) are, of course, vital prerequisites for secure food supplies. But they are not sufficient in themselves to address the range of factors involved, including issues of prioritisation in the event of restricted access to energy, water or transport (including ports and other trade routes).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra also commissioned a study by PricewaterhouseCoopers into the International Threats and Opportunities of Climate Change to the UK</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. In contrast to the National Programme, this highlights food as a major area of concern, pointing out that it needs to be considered in a global context, alongside water and energy as part of a food-water-energy system. It also drew attention to the extent to which the UK is reliant on its ability to source a diverse base of food supplies from abroad and the importance of affordability and access as well as availability. We very much agree with this analysis and believe it needs to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reflected in a much more strategic approach to risk and planning at Government level, with the help and involvement of food chain stakeholders.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The obstacles facing food producers, including small farmers, seeking to increase production and access new markets</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We believe that sustainable increases in production (from businesses of all sizes) are essential to meet future demand and address the risks associated with climate change. But this can only be achieved by a competitive and profitable food and farming sector with access to the science and technology needed to find innovative ways forward. This requires a policy and regulatory framework which supports industry’s efforts and provides a level playing field, particularly in terms of financial incentives for investment in research and development and a world class science and skills base.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In respect of exports, FDF worked with Defra and UKTI on the “UK Food and Drink International Action Plan”</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which sets targets for increasing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> food and drink exports by £1 bi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">llion by 2015 and assisting 1,000 businesses to grow internationally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. In collaboration with the Food and Drink Exporters Association (FDEA) we have also published a 10 step Guide to Export Success</span><a name="_ftnref28"></a><a href="#_ftn28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and ran the first sector focus week on food and drink on OpentoExport.com.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> But more needs to be done, not only in respect of support for exporters themselves, but also to help reduce the many tariff and non-tariff barriers to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rade which characterise the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> sector.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Ways of increasing self-sufficiency in products for which the UK has a comparative advantage</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is one of the issues addressed in the Defra Green Food Project to which FDF contributed. It is also one of the key aims of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Agri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-Tech strategy. From a manufacturing perspective, our primary concern is with the continued availability of high quality raw materials at competitive prices from safe, secure and traceable supply chains. It follows that in an era of increasingly volatile and potentially vulnerable global production, shortening supply chains and sourcing closer to home is likely to provide a greater degree of assurance in these respects. Manufacturers are increasingly working with dedicated supply chain partners and investing in increased resilience as well as the potential for future growth.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">10 December 2013</span></p></div><br style="clear:both; mso-break-type:section-break; page-break-before:always" /><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The UK Food and Drink Manufacturing Industry</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Food and Drink Federation (FDF) represents the food and drink manufacturing industry, the largest manufacturing sector in the UK, employing 400,000 people.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The industry has an annual turnover of over £78.7bn accounting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for 15% of the total manufacturing sector. Exports amount to over £12bn of which 76% goes to EU members. The industry buys two-thirds of all UK’s agricultural produce.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The following Associations actively work with the Food and Drink Federation:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ABIM</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Association of Bakery Ingredient Manufacturers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ACFM</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Association of Cereal Food Manufacturers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BCA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">British Coffee Association</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BOBMA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">British Oats and Barley Millers Association</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BSIA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">British Starch Industry Association</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BSNA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">British Specialist Nutrition Association</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="f